         <abstract>
            <p>The investment manager today faces a real dilemma--he is under pressure to improve investment performance at a time when the attainment of good results seems to be increasingly difficult and the risks particularly high. The task is, in many cases, complicated by the sheer size of funds under management. While most investors are committed to common stocks as the most satisfactory outlet for funds in what appears to be an inevitably inflationary economy, there is a very legitimate question on many investors' minds as to whether the current "performance" mania is one more fad that will pass or whether it has some substance. This article attempts to define performance, and give some brief thoughts on how the portfolio manager might react to it.</p>
          </abstract>
